  <h2>Effective Pest Management in Farming</h2>
  <b>
    Pests can cause significant loss to crops and affect overall farm productivity. 
    Effective pest control ensures healthier plants, higher yields, and reduces the need for excessive chemical pesticides. 
    Integrated Pest Management (IPM) combines biological, cultural, and chemical methods to manage pests sustainably.
  </b>
  <br><br>

  <div class="section">
    <h3>Why Pest Control Matters?</h3>
    <p>
        Pest control is crucial for maintaining crop health, preventing diseases, and securing food supply. Uncontrolled pests can damage leaves, stems, and roots, leading to reduced growth and lower production. 
        Proper pest management protects the environment and reduces economic losses for farmers.
    </p>
    <br>
    <b>Benefits of Effective Pest Control</b>
    <ul>
      <li>Healthy crops: Prevents crop damage and ensures better growth.</li>
      <li>Higher yield: Reduces losses caused by insects and pathogens.</li>
      <li>Economic savings: Minimizes cost of chemical pesticides.</li>
      <li>Environmental protection: Encourages natural pest predators and reduces chemical pollution.</li>
      <li>Food security: Ensures consistent production of safe and healthy crops.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h3>Integrated Pest Management (IPM)</h3>
    <img src="http://agsci.oregonstate.edu/sites/agscid7/files/ipm_click_1.jpg" alt="Pest control" class="img-center">
    <p>
        Integrated Pest Management (IPM) is an eco-friendly approach to pest control that combines cultural, mechanical, biological, and chemical methods. 
        IPM aims to reduce pest populations while minimizing risks to humans, animals, and the environment.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Biological control: Using natural predators like ladybugs and parasitic wasps.</li>
      <li>Cultural control: Crop rotation, planting pest-resistant varieties.</li>
      <li>Mechanical control: Traps, barriers, and manual removal of pests.</li>
      <li>Chemical control: Targeted pesticide use when necessary.</li>
      <li>Monitoring: Regular inspection of crops for early pest detection.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

